    public Object logExecutionTime(ProceedingJoinPoint joinPoint) throws Throwable {
        long startTime = System.currentTimeMillis();
        Object result = joinPoint.proceed();
        long endTime = System.currentTimeMillis();
        System.out.println("Method " + joinPoint.getSignature().getName() + " executed in " + (endTime - startTime) + " ms");
        return result;
    }
}
```

In this example, the `@Around` advice is used to intercept all method executions, measure the execution time, and print the result to the console. The `@Around` annotation specifies that this advice should be executed around the target method, and the `proceed()` method is used to call the original method.

**AspectJ Annotations**

AspectJ provides a set of annotations that can be used to define aspects. Here are some of the most commonly used annotations:

*   `@Aspect`: This annotation is used to indicate that a class is an aspect.
*   `@Before`: This annotation is used to define a pointcut that will be executed before the target method.
*   `@After`: This annotation is used to define a pointcut that will be executed after the target method.
*   `@AfterReturning`: This annotation is used to define a pointcut that will be executed after the target method returns.
*   `@AfterThrowing`: This annotation is used to define a pointcut that will be executed if the target method throws an exception.
*   `@Around`: This annotation is used to define a pointcut that will be executed around the advised method.

